COMM 3710: Presenting Research

Some Guidelines for Writing and Presenting Research

What is your story?

Your research tells a story. Before you start writing paper or creating a research presentation, you should have an outlinein mind.

The Anatomy of a Scientific Paper/Presentation


We will use the following journal article as an example:

Yeo, S. K., Su, L. Y.-F., Cacciatore, M. A., McKasy, M., & Qian, S. (2020). Predicting intentions to engage with scientific messages on Twitter: The roles of mirth and need for humor. Science Communication, 42(4), 481507. https://doi.org/10.1177/1075547020942512

Obtain a PDF of the article using the library resources available through the Marriott Library.

Of course, your presentation should always include a descriptive title and the authors names.

Introduction

Introduce the problem and the context of your research, i.e., set the stage for your study. You can do so by briefly describing the social significance of your research question/problem.


Describe the academic or scholarly significance of the research that you are presenting.


Identify the specific contribution of your study to the existing body of scholarly work and/or social context.

Literature Review and Rationale

In this section, you should review the existing scholarship that is relevant to your research question. The review of the literature often covers the key concepts in your study and often culminates with specific hypotheses and/or research questions.

An example of this can be seen below:


The literature review should contain brief descriptions of theories that are applicable to your study. This is part of the rationale of your study.

Method

The Method section describes the what and how of your research. In other words, it is the operationalization of your researchit is often the easiest section to write since it is a literal description of what you did in the study. It should include a description of your sample, the experimental design (if your study is experimental), the measures used in the study, and the data analysis.

As you can see in the Yeo et al. (2020) article, the first paragraph of the Method section describes the sample:


Then, a detailed description of the experiment is included in the article:


This is followed by a description of how the key variables that represent important concepts in the paper were measured or operationalized:


Results

In this section, you will use the data to address the hypotheses and research questions that you posed in the Literature Review and Rationale. You should use tables and figures as appropriate.
